Interacting with files - permissions

- File permissions are present in all file systems
- Linux handles permission based on 2 concepts:

1. who? User, group, or other
2. What? Read, write, or execute/run/open

- Each permission is given a score

- Read = 4
- Write = 2
- Run = 1

- So, if I want to give a user read access, give them 4, if they want read/write, give them 6, to run, give them 7, etc.

Example: If I run command permissions basic.txt output == 755

- So we know user (first digit = 7) has total priv to do anything
- Group has Read & execute (cannot change)
- Others have Read & Excecute
- If the permission number was 740 - we know user has full priv, group has read, other has no privileges to the file

![](data:image/png;base64,)

D stands for directory

Rwx = user has read/write/run priv

-rx = group has read/execute priv
